  "texts": [
    "The key contributions of this work are as follows:• Presentation of the most relevant scientific models for Cloud, Cloud-Edge, and federated Continuum systems.",
    "• Identification of significant gaps in existing literature in the context of energy-aware Cloud-Edge system models.• 2 Background: modeling cloud systemsThe architectural landscape of Cloud and Edge systems has evolved rapidly over time, transitioning from ''traditional'' non-federated Cloud systems to Cloud-Edge architectures, and eventually advancing to federated Continuum systems.It is beneficial to first explore the conceptual nature of these approaches before investigating the modeling behind them.",
    "Traditional cloud systemsIn a non-federated ''traditional'' cloud system, a single cloud service provider typically manages one or more geographically dispersed data center sites.",
    "A typical geo- distributed cloud data center environment [13] integrating a single cloud service provider, multiple end-users, and several energy sources is shown in Fig. 2.Here, the cloud service provider manages several geographically distributed data center sites (DCs).",
    "To offer services and resources to cloud consumers, each DC is linked to a backbone network and makes use of a variety of energy sources such as the commercial grid (brown energy) and green energy sources, networking and power equipment, and other devices."
  ]
}